 Mobile App solutions\">Become a Client</a></li>\r\n	<li><a class=\"contact colour-white type-lowercase type-semibold family-table\" href=\"/get-in-contact\" title=\"Enquire for eCommerce, Website Design and Mobile App solutions\">Let&rsquo;s Talk?</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1140,'Main Body','<div class=\"cols more-posts\">\n    		<div class=\"col newsfeed-entry entry-1\">\n			<div class=\"news-img\" style=\"background-image:url(\'http://www.chriswatterston.com/application/files/cache/c0a53e1750181cc2a437e87408ce6f41.jpg\');\"></div>\n			<div class=\"news-content-wrap\">\n				<div class=\"news-content\">\n                    	<h2 class=\"colour-grey type-semibold\">Progress on &lsquo;SKOOLping&rsquo; and why there&#039;s been a substantial delay?</h2>\n          					<p class=\"description colour-grey\">\n													Two steps forward, one step back. It seems with all startups there are hurdles to jump through and bridges to climb, with every step of progress. It just happens that the brand I have come to create for our communication app&hellip;											</p>\n				</div>\n			</div>\n			<a href=\"http://www.chriswatterston.com/blog/progress-on-skoolping-and-why-theres-been-a-substantial-delay\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Continue reading, Progress on &lsquo;SKOOLping&rsquo; and why there&#039;s been a substantial delay?\" class=\"hidden\"></a>\n		</div>\n			<div class=\"col newsfeed-entry entry-2\">\n			<div class=\"news-img\" style=\"background-image:url(\'http://www.chriswatterston.com/application/files/cache/33b45f3a8a884e9ecf07e6037ed9093c.jpg\');\"></div>\n			<div class=\"news-content-wrap\">\n				<div class=\"news-content\">\n                    	<h2 class=\"colour-grey type-semibold\">My new bespoke embossed kraft business cards</h2>\n          					<p class=\"description colour-grey\">\n													It had just passed my 2 year anniversary of working as a self employed designer, so thought I&rsquo;d treat myself to some brand spanking new creative business cards, aka &lsquo;give outs&rsquo;. My old ones were boring, to plain. I wanted&hellip;											</p>\n				</div>\n			</div>\n			<a href=\"http://www.chriswatterston.com/case-studies/my-new-bespoke-embossed-kraft-business-cards\" target=\"_self\" title=\"Continue reading, My new bespoke embossed kraft business cards\" class=\"hidden\"></a>\n		</div>\n	</div>\n',1513306614),(240,5,1196,'Main Body','<img src=\"/application/files/5615/1150/9770/tut-createpfx-step1.jpg\" alt=\"Certificate CSR Example\" width=\"717\" height=\"652\" class=\"ccm-image-block img-responsive bID-1196\" title=\"Certificate CSR Example\">',1669277111),(240,5,1200,'Main Body','<img src=\"/application/files/7115/1143/9383/tut-import-step2.jpg\" alt=\"Complete CSR\" width=\"631\" height=\"510\" class=\"ccm-image-block img-responsive bID-1200\" title=\"Complete CSR\">',1669277111),(240,5,1203,'Main Body','<img src=\"/application/files/3115/1143/9389/tut-export-step3.jpg\" alt=\"Export PFX file SSL\" width=\"623\" height=\"576\" class=\"ccm-image-block img-responsive bID-1203\" title=\"Export PFX file SSL\">',1669277111),(240,5,1204,'Main Body','<img src=\"/application/files/3515/1143/9387/tut-pass-step5.jpg\" alt=\"Import PFX into Microsoft Azure\" width=\"438\" height=\"348\" class=\"ccm-image-block img-responsive bID-1204\" title=\"Import PFX into Microsoft Azure\">',1669277111),(240,5,1207,'Main Body','<p><a href=\"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-gb/\" name=\"Microsoft Azure\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Microsoft Azure\">Microsoft Azure</a> is a very powerful cloud computing service created by Microsoft for building, testing, deploying, and managing applications and services through a global network of Microsoft-managed data centres. Microsoft initially released Azure in 2010, and since has&nbsp;grown massively&nbsp;and is continuing to grow and change every single day.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1208,'Main Body','<h3>1. Generating a Certificate Signing Request (CSR)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe nature in which Azure is build on (a cloud service), means that the&nbsp;CSR and private key cannot be generated on the <a href=\"http://www.chriswatterston.com/blog/my-there-is-no-cloud-sticker\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"There is no Cloud\">&ldquo;cloud&rdquo; server</a>. Instead, we need to use our own physical, or <a class=\"Virtual Machine\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_machine\" target=\"_blank\">virtual&nbsp;machine</a>. I&rsquo;m a daily Mac user, so like to use a &lsquo;Windows 10&rsquo; virtual machine to perform this type of task.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOpen the Windows application&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.iis.net/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Internet Information Services (IIS)\">Internet Information Services (IIS)</a> and select &lsquo;Server Certificates&rsquo; within the root &lsquo;Connections&rsquo; tree list. Over on the right within the &lsquo;Actions&rsquo; panel, select &lsquo;Create Certificate Request&rsquo; - continue following the onscreen instructions until you have saved and opened up your TXT file in front of you.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1209,'Main Body','<h3>2. Submitting CSR to a Certificate&nbsp;Authority&nbsp;(CA)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nOnce you have <a href=\"https://uk.godaddy.com/web-security/ssl-certificate\" name=\"purchased an SSL certificate for you preferred CA\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"purchased an SSL certificate for you preferred CA\">purchased an SSL certificate for you preferred CA</a>, you&rsquo;ll be required to submit your CSR into their system. Every CA will have a slightly different process to follow, but it should be faily simple...<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNow that you&rsquo;ve submitted your CSR, you will likely be required to complete some kind of &lsquo;Domain Access Verification&rsquo;. This is normaly achieved by adding a TXT record into the domain&rsquo;s DNS, in which you are purchasing and applying the SSL against.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<b>BUT I want to create a PFX for an existing SSL certificate</b> - That&rsquo;s cool. Instead of buying a new SSL, you&#39;ll just need to &lsquo;Rekey&rsquo; your existing certificate. You can do this by re-submitting a new CSR to the CA. Every CA have different methods, but it should still a simple process.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1210,'Main Body','<h3>3. Downloading and Importing Certificate</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nNow that you have successfully completed all the domain verification processes, you will now be able to download your certificate files. Some CA&#39;s allow you to do this in a number of different formats (Exchange, Apache, ISS, etx). It&rsquo;s normally good practice to download the files for the method you used to create the CSR, therefor I will be downloading the files for IIS.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter downloading, extract the ZIPPED files onto your Desktop. Back within IIS, under the &lsquo;Actions&rsquo; panel as before, select &lsquo;Complete Certificate Request&rsquo;. Located and select the certificate file (.crt) which you download within the ZIPPED file, enter a recognisable and friendly name and click &lsquo;Ok&rsquo;.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1211,'Main Body','<h3>4. Exporting PFX ready for Azure</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nYou should now be able to see your imported certificate within the IIS &lsquo;Server Certificates&rsquo; list. Let&rsquo;s move onto exporting the all important and required PFX file for Azure.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOpen up console by typing &lsquo;mmc&rsquo; into &lsquo;Run&rsquo; (Windows + R). Within the console, click &lsquo;File&rsquo; and &lsquo;Add/Remove Snap-ins&hellip;&rsquo;.&nbsp; Select and add &lsquo;Certificates&rsquo;, choosing to manage for &lsquo;Computer Accounts&rsquo; during the process.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter loading the &lsquo;Certificates&rsquo; Snap-in, within the console tree list, expand &lsquo;Certificates &gt; Personal &gt; Certificates&rsquo;. You should now see your certificate listed. Right Click the certificate, and Select &lsquo;All Tasks &gt; Export&hellip;&rsquo;. During the process, make sure that you select &lsquo;Yes&rsquo; when asked to export the private key and that the following options are selected - ensure that the option &lsquo;Delete the private key if the export is successful&rsquo; is UNSELECTED ...otherwise this whole process is a waste of time :)<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<b>NOTE:</b> During the process, ensure that you give your exported PFX a strong password. But remember to write it down as you&rsquo;ll need to when you import into Azure.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1212,'Main Body','<h3>5. Importing PFX into Azure</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Congratulation! Now that you have your PFX file ready and waiting, we can now&nbsp;import straight into Azure.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<a href=\"https://portal.azure.com/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Sign into Azure account\">Sign into your Azure account</a>, select the App you wish to apply the SSL against and open &lsquo;SSL Certificates&rsquo;. Select &lsquo;Upload Certificate&rsquo; and browse for the PFX (.pfx) file you created, making sure you enter&nbsp;your strong password&nbsp;- and finally finish by clicking &lsquo;Upload&rsquo;.</p>\r\n',1669277119),(240,5,1213,'Main Body','<p>You can now continue to add SSL Binding to your web app, or apps&nbsp;if you have a wildcard, to enable your site to use the certificate and load as HTTPS - well done :)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Credits: Photography&nbsp; by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://unsplash.com/photos/bqGBbLq_yfc?utm_source=unsplash&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_content=creditCopyText\">John Salvino</a>&nbsp;on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://unsplash.com/?utm_source=unsplash&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_content=creditCopyText\">Unsplash</a></p>\r\n',1669277119),(241,1,47,'Main','<h1 class=\"colour-white type-semibold type-uppercase\">Contact.</h1>\r\n',1669337044),(241,1,51,'Main','<h1 class=\"colour-white type-semibold type-uppercase\">Instagram.</h1>\r\n',1669337045),(241,1,62,'Main','<ul class=\"nav\"><li class=\"\">