on 1 - shipping</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>My primary shipping service is <a href=\"http://www.royalmail.com/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Royal Mail\">Royal Mail</a> or ParcelForce Worldwide. Both are services that are operated by Royal Mail Group Limited. Most of my products ship from from our business location in Middlesex, UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every product is usually shipped within two (2) days, but generally within 24 hours. Deliveries will be made within 1 to 10 working days dependant upon weight and service requested. I do my best to ship items out as quickly as possible, so I often get orders out more quickly than is noted by the timeframe stated. Additionally, please note that delivery time is also based on &quot;business&quot; days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I do not profit from shipping, but prices within your invoice may differ compaired that of the offical shipping service.&nbsp;If we&#39;re shipping your order within the UK or internationally, your shipping cost are likely to be the same as we are charged by whichever shipping company is used to deliver your package. Shipping costs are calculated on the website automatically during checkout based on the weight of the items you are purchasing. While an effort is made to&nbsp;try and keep shipping costs up-to-date, I cannot guarantee this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Delivery will be made to the delivery address submitted at time of purchase. If your delivery address has been submitted incorrectly, you must contact me within 4 hours of your purchase to update us with your correct delivery address.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If a customer inputs any incorrect address details on their order, which causes the parcel to be delivered incorrectly. I will not hold any responsibility for this parcel.ie, the customer will have to try and retrieve the parcel themselves at their cost.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If my shipping services are unable to gain access to the agreed delivery address, the shipping services&nbsp;will return the goods to a local/ our warehouse and make contact with you to re-arrange delivery.&nbsp; Unfortunately in these circumstances I may have to charge you a further delivery fee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Depending on chosen shipping, goods must be signed for to confirm receipt. If you are unavailable at this time, I recommend a responsible adult is available to sign on your behalf.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I do not send to PO BOX addresses.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Section 2 - Shipping Errors</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Shipping errors must be reported within 1 day of date of delivery. All orders, are checked and double checked before leaving for delivery. If you are a UK customer and you have not received your order within 7 days of dispatch date, then you must notify me within these 7 days. If you notify me after these 7 days then we will not be responsible for its location, and we may not be able to claim for the parcel if it lost/stolen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have received your parcel in poor condition/damaged or have items missing. You must keep all outer packaging so that the courier can collect the parcel for their investigation.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Section 3 - Returns</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>You have 14 calendar days to return an item from the date you received it. To be eligible for a return, your item must be unused and in the same condition that you received it.&nbsp;Your item must be in the original unopened shipping packaging. Your item needs to have the receipt or proof of purchase.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Section 4 - Refunds</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I have received your item, it will be inspected and you will be notified that I have received your returned item. I will immediately notify you on the status of your refund after inspecting the item.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your return is approved, I will initiate a refund to your original method of payment. You will receive the credit within a certain amount of days, depending on your original payment method issuer&#39;s policies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will be responsible for paying for your own shipping costs for returning your item. Shipping costs are non&shy;refundable. If you receive a refund, the cost of return shipping will be deducted from your refund.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Section 5 - Contact Information</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This website is owned and operated by myself,&nbsp;Chris Watterston.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My principal place of business is at &lsquo;Pentire - Stable 2, Fordbridge Road, Sunbury-on-Thames, Middlesex, TW16 6AX, United Kingdom&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Questions about the Terms of Service should be sent to me at <a href=\"mailto:hello@chriswatterston.com\">hello@chriswatterston.com</a>.</p>\r\n'),(954,'<h2><strong>IMPORTANT:</strong> This policy is for products printed and distributed through this website&nbsp;by myself, Chris Watterston. This policy does not apply to third-parties such as, but not limited to; Sticker Mule, Spreadshirt and &nbsp;Society6.</h2>\r\n'),(955,'<p class=\"colour-white family-table\">Copyright &copy; 2017 Chris Watterston. All rights reserved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"colour-white family-table\"><a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_217}\" title=\"Cookie Policy\">Cookie Policy</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_218}\" title=\"Terms of Use\">Terms of Use</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_219}\" title=\"Accessibility\">Accessibility</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"{CCM:CID_220}\" title=\"Store and products terms\">Store &amp; Products Terms</a></p>\r\n'),(956,'<h1 class=\"colour-white\"><strong>Shipping, Returns and Refund Policy.</strong> Store &amp; Products.</h1>\r\n'),(957,'<p class=\"colour-white family-table\">Copyright &copy; 2017 Chris Watterston. All rights reserved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"colour-white family-table\"><a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_217}\" title=\"Cookie Policy\">Cookie Policy</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_218}\" title=\"Terms of Use\">Terms of Use</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_219}\" title=\"Accessibility\">Accessibility</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"{CCM:CID_220}\" title=\"Store and products policy\">Store &amp; Products Policy</a></p>\r\n'),(958,'<p class=\"colour-white family-table\">Copyright &copy; 2017 Chris Watterston. All rights reserved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"colour-white family-table\"><a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_217}\" title=\"Cookie Policy\">Cookie Policy</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_218}\" title=\"Terms of Use\">Terms of Use</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a class=\"colour-white\" href=\"{CCM:CID_219}\" title=\"Accessibility\">Accessibility</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"{CCM:CID_220}\" title=\"Store policy\">Store Policy</a></p>\r\n'),(959,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>As an overall conclusion, I feel my vision of how I wanted my business cards was a success - everything turned out as expected. It goes to prove that with the right materials, suppliers and a bit of time, real bespoke one of a kind ideas can turn into something great!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A massive thank you to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.exaprint.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\">Exaprint.co.uk</a>&nbsp;for the bespoke labels and embosser, and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.printed.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Printer.com</a>&nbsp;for the Kraft business cards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(961,'<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve learned a lesson that I previously knew, but never&nbsp;actually put it into practice until now. You should never let a supplier or designer put you off your vision&nbsp;just becaue it&#39;s not available &quot;on the shelf&quot;. You source the materials, from different suppliers if needed, and you put your own touch and time into combining materials to create something unique and quite special.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(962,'<h3>Project goal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I had an open goal, but a vision. My vision was to create a business card for myself which looked great, felt great, had quality&nbsp;smeared all over it, but also was branded, unique and nothing else alike. I wanted the business cards to also feel like they had a &quot;hand crafted&quot; feeling. Let the challenge begin!</p>\r\n'),(965,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The end results surprised everyone, bringing smiles to staff, students and parents. A colourful, exciting and fully responsive website&nbsp;which works on any device. From TV&rsquo;s to the smallest of smartphone screens, at all orientation.</p>\r\n'),(966,'<h3>Project goal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Our goal for Heathside School&#39;s website project was relatively simple. With a strong brand and colouring now in place, a website was required to help push the new look publicly - we dived at the challenge.</p>\r\n'),(971,'<p>My partner and I weighed up a couple of options, but what we settled on would give a bit of fun for John (and place me in my&nbsp;<a data-concrete5-link-type=\"ajax\" href=\"{CCM:CID_201}\" title=\"essence\">essence</a>). We decided to take what we know John socially loves to enjoy, give it a personal twist and&nbsp;<a data-concrete5-link-type=\"ajax\" href=\"{CCM:CID_159}\" title=\"print\">print</a>&nbsp;it onto 94mm square 1.2mm uncoated beer mats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes that perfect gift can&#39;t be picked from a&nbsp;shelf, bit it will never be 110% unique and &quot;made&quot; for that person. It takes a careful&nbsp;thought process, knowing them personally&nbsp;and&nbsp;understanding what they love to enjoy and how they&#39;ll use the gift. We&nbsp;feel it couldn&#39;t of turned out any better - bringing a smile to John every time he lifts his pint of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guinness.com/en-gb/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Guinness\">Guinness</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What do you think, leave a comment - have you seen something to inspire you?</strong></p>\r\n'),(978,'<h3>Project goal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Duncan, the director of Tesla Installations Ltd approched me in January 2014, when his new business was just an idea. He wanted to fulfill a dream of his, to start and build a succussful electrical business. Because it was very early, the startup had no personality to use within it&#39;s branding - but it had a vision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Duncan and I wanted to create his brand with roots which were&nbsp;scalable, strong, and recognisable. Duncan knew what he wanted his company to be called, and knew that he wanted a red logo, the rest was left to me.</p>\r\n'),(980,'<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Tesla Installations Ltd was one my first offical&nbsp;startups what I worked with, I had never <em>really</em> created a complete brand for a startup before. &nbsp;The learning curve was sheer and speedy, but I was in my prime. I thrive to be thown into the deep end to find my feet, so to speak. I enjoyed every second while designing Duncan&#39;s brand from his vision, the excitment was clearly apparent from Duncan and myself the more the project progressed.</p>\r\n'),(981,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Working directly with the Director of Tesla Installations, we introduced some concept ideas and&nbsp;designs, from which we then collaborated and build what is Tesla Installations&#39; brand today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From and finalised Tesla Installations brand, we continued to developed their&nbsp;brand with guidelines, vehicle signwriting, business cards&nbsp;content management system&nbsp;<em>(CMS)</em>&nbsp;integrated website, and mush more.</p>\r\n'),(982,'<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Tesla Installations Ltd was one my first offical&nbsp;startups what I worked with, I had never <em>really</em> created a complete brand for a startup before. &nbsp;The learning curve was sheer and speedy, but I was in my essence. I thrive to be thown into the deep end to find my feet, so to speak. I enjoyed every second while designing Duncan&#39;s brand from his vision, the excitment was clearly apparent from Duncan and myself the more the project progressed.</p>\r\n'),(984,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Working directly with Duncan at&nbsp;Tesla Installations Ltd, we introduced some concept ideas and&nbsp;designs, from which we then collaborated and build what is Tesla Installations&#39; brand today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From and finalised brand, we continued to developed their&nbsp;brand with guidelines, vehicle signwriting, business cards, content management system&nbsp;<em>(CMS)</em>&nbsp;integrated website, and much more.&nbsp;It was fantastic to work, watch and experience Tesla Installations Ltd grow and develop into a trusted and reliable electrician service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a class=\"abtn black\" href=\"http://teslainstallations.com\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Find out more\">Find out more, visit their website</a></p>\r\n'),(988,'<h3>Project goal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Designated PA contacted me in the middle of January 2015 and asked me to&nbsp;redesign their logo&nbsp;and ensure that it brings a new, exciting and more professional quality to their business. I jumped at the opportunity.</p>\r\n'),(991,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Working with the Director of Designated PA, I took their vision and values and produced 10&nbsp;concept logo designs&nbsp;from which we collaborated and agreed to a single design that really brought their businesses qualities to the public eye.</p>\r\n'),(993,'<p>Working and collaborating directly with the Technical Director, a solid and meaningful brand was born. The&nbsp;master&nbsp;brand iconic logo&nbsp;has been designed to represent the circle and arrangement of the obtainable services offered, reaching to surrounding areas. Truly&nbsp;genius.</p>\r\n'),(1007,'<p>We&rsquo;ve had the privilege of supporting Saint Michael Catholic Primary School in Ashford for many years, but pushing their previous outdated website to the side and redesigning their websites has been the recent highlight - it&rsquo;s been great bring their website back to life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a class=\"abtn black\" href=\"http://www.st-michaels.surrey.sch.uk/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Find out more, visit their website\">Find out more, visit their website</a></p>\r\n'),(1022,'<p>Saint John Bosco College also told me that they were expecting to move into a brand new school, based in London Battersea, in September 2015. With the launch of this fantastic and exciting news and bringing together a brand new fresh online experience for visitors, and presence for their school and college, everything was fantastic.</p>\r\n'),(1029,'<p>Wood Street Capital are an independent UK based turnaround investor and private equity specialist focusing on financial investment and the provision of hands-on operational expertise to businesses facing stress, distress or other special situations. I received an email from a marketing manager in the middle of March 2014, asking for&nbsp;complete branding&nbsp;and&nbsp;website design&nbsp;for a new up and coming business investor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After hours of designing and collaboration with their&nbsp;partners and marketing manager, I united Wood Street Capital with their solid and meaningful brand. Delivering their message of love for capitalising turnaround and growth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Agreeing their logo design and guidelines, a large array of&nbsp;brand&nbsp;materials&nbsp;were designed. Such as business cards, CD covers and&nbsp;sleeves, letterhead, compliment slips, envelops, folders, invoice and quotations, seasonal greeting card,&nbsp;HTML marketing templates, iOS home screen icon, stickers and much more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To tell the truth, I really enjoy working with startups just as much as an already up and running organisation. I love to see and hear their passion and excitement, and really get a kick out of seeing them succeed.</p>\r\n'),(1031,'<p>Salesian School are a friendly and active school, with a bright future. They take on students aged from 11 to 18 years of age, with a Catholic background.&nbsp;The overall outcome was somewhat of a clever attention grabber. With animated buttons using the latest web technology and a strong colourful colour palette, it was like building with lego bricks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a class=\"abtn black\" href=\"http://www.salesian.surrey.sch.uk/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Find out more, visit their website\">Find out more, visit their website</a></p>\r\n'),(1039,'<p>Moorfields Corporate Recovery are one of&nbsp;UK&#39;s leading firms, providing Corporate Advisory, Restructuring and Insolvency Services in London, UK.&nbsp;I&#39;ve seen Moorfields grow as a business. Officially&nbsp;from of RSM Bentley Jennison, breaking away to become a&nbsp;limited liability partnership (LLP) called&nbsp;Moorfields&nbsp;Corporate Recovery, then later becoming a limited company (LTD) in 2014. Moorfields Corporate Recovery have worked with businesses such as Blockbuster,&nbsp;Teknoflex Ltd and&nbsp;TNT Magazine - they&#39;ve also won quite a few&nbsp;awards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve enjoyed working along side the staff of&nbsp;Salesian School, helping them meet their visions and goals.</p>\r\n'),(1048,'<h3>Project goal</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The across the board goal was to ensure that CD Surveys fleet of vans could be recognised as theirs, no questions. It would include their logo, colouring, real essential contact and finally their services. The design also naturally had to work on other vans if need be, effectively a future proof design.</p>\r\n'),(1049,'<h3 id=\"focus-on-process-before-artifact\">Process&nbsp;and research&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I presented a few thought out ideas, which grew to what is todays design. To help CD Surveys Ltd visualise, I took a photograph of one of their new vehicles and &lsquo;Photoshopped&rsquo; how the final design would look like. This reassured CD Surveys Ltd in how the final outcome would be and feel, before progressing onto organisation of the application. Everything went perfectly smooth.</p>\r\n'),(1050,'<h3>Lessons Learned</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>During the early stages of creating the design concepts, we learnt that simplicity on small vehicles can be massive - simple in design, but big in impression. Using the bold colours already present within the CD Surveys Ltd logo, really helped to portray this impression, effectively &ldquo;extending&rdquo; the logo through the vehicle body to give the feeling of a bigger logo than what is actually.</p>\r\n'),(1051,'<h3>Conclusion</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The project as a&nbsp;whole took approximately 2 months to complete, this was from CD Surveys Ltd first conversation with us, through to the vehicles being driven around. Projects like this can vary in project scale, but this was a small/medium project that I really enjoyed. Even more that I witnessed their previous fleet of poorly sign written vehicle move onto new owners. The CD Surveys Ltd team love their new vehicles, and so do I.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a class=\"abtn black\" href=\"http://www.cdsurveys.com\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Find out more, visit their website\">Find out more, visit their website</a></p>\r\n'),(1055,'<h3>Testimonial</h3>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>We commissioned Chris Watterston and his design capabilities to create and add a &lsquo;stand out&rsquo; livery for our 4 new Ford vans.<br />\r\nI can honestly say the result was outstanding and is very eye catching&hellip; even on the roof&hellip;<br />\r\nDue to this excellent work we have subsequently commissioned Chris to undertake a review of our Web pages then he<br />\r\nmoved onto our business cards. Both again very stunning results.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nGreat chap, great business, great ideas&hellip;.. will certainly use Chris again and recommend him to all my colleagues</blockquote>\r\n'),(1056,'<h2><strong>Every design or development project are non-identical. These require&nbsp;different tactical methods with slightly different solutions -&nbsp;each completed with passion and determination.&nbsp;Here are a few of my clients projects that not only delivered great client satisfaction, but have exceeded the above and beyond.</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Join our conversation online and&nbsp;<a data-concrete5-link-lightbox=\"iframe\" href=\"http://eepurl.com/bfCjXj\" target=\"lightbox\" title=\"subscribe\">subscribe&nbsp;to receive our monthly newsletters</a>.<br />\r\nI&rsquo;ll only email you with important bits, never spam - that&#39;s a&nbsp;pinky promise!</p>\r\n'),(1057,'<ul>\r\n	<li><a class=\"contact colour-white type-lowercase type-semibold family-table\" href=\"/designer-developer-solutions-and-services\" title=\"eCommerce, Website Designer and Mobile App solutions\">Become a Client</a></li>\r\n	<li><a class=\"contact colour-white type-lowercase type-semibold family-table\" href=\"/get-in-contact\" title=\"Enquire for eCommerce, Website Design and Mobile App solutions\">Let&rsquo;s Talk?</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n'),(1058,'<h2 class=\"colour-white\"><strong>The Original.</strong> The Unique.<br />\r\n#TherIsNoCloud</h2>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"colour-white\">Never in a million years did I expect <a href=\"/blog/there-no-cloud-getting-1-sticker-mule-marketplace\" title=\"my sticker, There is No Cloud\">my sticker, &lsquo;There is No Cloud&rsquo;</a>, to go the way it did. It&rsquo;s just a pretty simple 8.13 x 6.45 cm die cut sticker. But unbelievably it went global!&nbsp;Over 20,000 printed units sold globally, the words are spreading far and wide.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"colour-white\">&quot;There is no cloud. It&#39;s just someone else&#39;s computer&quot; It&#39;s only the truth, but I wonder how many people really think there really is a &quot;cloud&quot; that stores all our data?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a class=\"abtn grey small\" href=\"/blog/my-there-is-no-cloud-sticker\" title=\"find out more about \'There is no Cloud\' design\">More about the &#39;There is no Cloud&#39; design</a> <a class=\"abtn grey small\" href=\"/store\" title=\"See our products and gifts which include There is no Cloud\">Shop &#39;There is no Cloud&#39; products</a></p>\r\n'),(1059,'<p>This particular personal family project begin back in October 2016, when my partner, Georgina, and I talked about buying our daughters a &ldquo;girly&rdquo; Wendy playhouse for them to play in and store their toys in. I initially agreed and became fond of the idea, but having Scottish in my blood, I started to become against the idea, the idea of buying something I knew I could build. I also think most playhouses on the market are rather boring, they are basically all similar to one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the end, we both agreed that I&rsquo;d build our daughters a playhouse. I yearn for letting my creative juices flow while having fun - let&rsquo;s build a Hobbit Hole Playhouse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Around September 2016, the build started. The structure would have to withstand earth on top, people walking on top of it and damp surroundings. Because I planned on building an REAL miniature &ldquo;semi-under ground&rdquo; Hobbit Hole. Not a Hobbit styled garden shed.</p>\r\n'),(1061,'<h2><strong>Let&#39;s build.</strong></h2>\r\n'),(1062,'<p>I used an old 7&rsquo;sih metre 10mm RSJ steel beam for the main structural framework, this was perfect as it was strong, durable and workable. Cutting this down the middle then created 2 equal T-section style steel lengths, to then be aligned and welded together to create 2 trapezoid shape type frames. I then used another smaller 10mm RSJ steel beam to fix between the top sections of the trapezoids. I then strapped the frame up and lifted into were we wanted it, allowing me to mark on the grass which area would be excavated and how deep.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once we were happy with the placement and depth, I moved the structure to start excavation. I also installed a number of 8&rdquo;x2&rdquo; treated wooden lengths to the structure, enabling an easy base for when I start constructing the walls. After I was happy with the framework and structure knowing it was strong enough and safe enough, I moved onto the interior.</p>\r\n'),(1065,'<p>Naturally, being a Hobbit Hole the interior needed to look and feel natural too. I nipped to Wickes to pick up some Plywood and made a start on the interior. The sides and rear walls of the Hobbit Hole would be be covered in earth, so these were fitted inside and outside with 18mm chipboard. The front side wouldn&rsquo;t have any earth weight against it, so 9mm Plywood was used. The roofs exterior, like the sides and rear, had 18mm chipboard. For the roofs interior, I decided to make this a lighting feature and create a &lsquo;Star Ceiling&rsquo; effect. Instead of using a traditional optic fibre lighting to create the desired effect, instead I used the cheaper and tougher option of white LED Christmas lights. I first intended to have the stars scattered, but due to the structure and limitation of the lights and avoiding the wastage of valuable light as it&rsquo;s going to be a dark space, I decided to lay them out in a &lsquo;zig-zag&rsquo; and use every bulb. After approval from our eldest daughter, Ellie, I continued to mark every lights placement with a black dot and drilled a 4mm hole through the Plywood to home the lights, finally fixing with a glue gun.</p>\r\n'),(1068,'<p>Now that the &lsquo;Star Ceiling&rsquo; was built, tested and installed, it was time to lift the Hobbit Hole one last time and drop it into it&rsquo;s final resting place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The hole was lined with 1mm plastic as damp proofing, with the structure then placed inside of that, I continued to wrap the whole structure in the same plastic, excluding the front wall. I then used sections from an old chopped up glass fibre pond to help add extra strength and seal the top. Thankfully, when it came to filling the base and exteriors outer edges with roughly 200mm of concrete, we had my partners nephew, George, staying who saved a lot of heat, sweat and red faces - good man!</p>\r\n'),(1072,'<p>While the concrete we laid it in the morning was left to set and harden, during the afternoon, George and I decided to dig and run armoured cable into the Hobbit Hole. Throughout the week, I moved onto building and installing a Hobbit style door, sealed the exposed Plywood with liquid damp proofing and finally started to pile earth around the rear and sides. To control the lighting and ensure there was no exposed switches because children will be playing in it, I tucked all the electrical components and connections away in a secure wall box, fitted with a&nbsp; LightWaveRF inline relay. This means we could control the lighting by remote or through our smartphones.</p>\r\n'),(1075,'<p>Moving on, now that the concrete had set and safe enough to climb inside, it was time to decorate and create a feature wall. I decided on creating a feature wall which involved log slices, so I set-up the cradle and fired the McCulloch chainsaw into life. Cutting each slice of already seasoned wood at approximately the same thickness, I had to cut roughly 2 large buckets to have enough to complete the wall.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(1078,'<p>The Interior was now complete and working, it was damp proofed and grass was slowly but surely starting to growing on the roof and up the sides. Things were working out great! I now needed to cover the exposed blue plastic wrap around the front, doing this with an old corrugated roofing sheet. Cut to size and overlapped, secured with concrete, expandable foam and pop rivets - and finally finished off with a lick of brown paint to help blend in and look natural. I also created 2 log retaining walls to help hold back the earth, held together by large pins that are put through every log and then into the ground.</p>\r\n'),(1079,'<h2><strong>Thoughts on the final outcome</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Fast forward over 6 months, I&rsquo;m happy with how things look and worked out. This wasn&rsquo;t a step-by-step planned projects, it was merely a &lsquo;make it up as you go along&rsquo; kind of project with no deadlines (which makes a change). Projects like this give you the opportunity to chop and change ideas as you go, but at the same time can allow you to forget to do things that you should of done - but lucky for me I hadn&rsquo;t&hellip; I think?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The grass hasn&rsquo;t fully grown yet and is still a tad patchy, but it will grow in time. My partner has recently planted strawberries and scattered coloured wild flower seeds, so next year things should look even better. This is the type of project that looks better and more natural as time goes on, when nature tries to take over again.</p>\r\n'),(1082,'<h2><strong>Thoughts on the final outcome</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Fast forward over 6 months, I&rsquo;m happy with how things look and worked out. This wasn&rsquo;t a step-by-step planned projects, it was merely a &lsquo;make it up as you go along&rsquo; kind of project with no deadlines (which makes a change). Projects like this give you the opportunity to chop and change ideas as you go, but at the same time can allow you to forget to do things that you should of done - but lucky for me I hadn&rsquo;t&hellip; I think?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The grass hasn&rsquo;t fully grown yet and is still a tad patchy, but it will grow in time. My partner has recently planted strawberries and scattered coloured wild flower seeds, so next year things should look even better. This is the type of project that looks better and more natural as time goes on, when nature tries to take over again.</p>\r\n'),(1085,'<p>This particular personal family project begin back in October 2016, when my partner, Georgina, and I talked about buying our daughters a &ldquo;girly&rdquo; Wendy playhouse for them to play&nbsp;and store their toys in. I initially agreed and became quite fond of the idea, but having Scottish in my blood, I started to become against the idea. It was the&nbsp;idea of buying something I knew I could build. I also thought most playhouses on the market were rather boring, they were basically all very similar to one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the end, we both agreed that I&rsquo;d build our daughters a playhouse. I yearn for letting my creative juices flow while having fun - let&rsquo;s build a Hobbit Hole Playhouse!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Around September 2016, the build started. The structure would have to withstand earth being placed on top, people walking over it and damp surroundings. Because I planned on building an REAL miniature &ldquo;semi-under ground&rdquo; Hobbit Hole. Not a Hobbit styled garden shed.</p>\r\n'),(1086,'<p>I used an old 7&rsquo;sih metre 10mm RSJ steel beam for the main structural framework, this was perfect as it was strong, durable and workable. Cutting this down the middle then created 2 equal T-section steel lengths, to then be aligned and welded together to create 2 trapezoid shaped frames. I then used another smaller 10mm RSJ steel beam to fix between the top sections of the trapezoids. I then strapped the frame up and lifted into were we wanted it, allowing me to mark on the grass which area would be excavated and how deep.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once we were happy with the placement and depth, I moved the structure to start excavation a large hole 600mm deep. I also installed a number of 8&rdquo;x2&rdquo; treated wooden lengths to the structure, enabling an easy base for when I start constructing the walls. After I was happy with the framework and structure knowing it was strong enough and safe enough, I moved onto the interior.</p>\r\n'),(1087,'<p>Naturally, being a Hobbit Hole the interior needed to look and feel natural. I nipped to Wickes to pick up some Plywood and made a start on the interior. The sides and rear walls of the Hobbit Hole would be be covered in earth, so these were fitted inside and outside with 18mm chipboard. The front side wouldn&rsquo;t have any earth weight against it, so 9mm Plywood was used. The roofs exterior, like the sides and rear, had 18mm chipboard. For the roofs interior, I decided to make this a lighting feature and create a &lsquo;Star Ceiling&rsquo; effect. Instead of using a traditional optic fibre lighting system to create the desired effect, instead I used the cheaper and tougher option of white LED Christmas lights. I first intended to have the stars scattered, but due to the structure and limitation of the lights and avoiding the wastage of valuable light, since it was going to be quite&nbsp;a dark space, I decided to lay them out in a &lsquo;zig-zag&rsquo; and use every available bulb. After approval from our eldest daughter, Ellie, I continued to mark every lights placement with a black dot and drilled a 4mm hole through the Plywood to home the lights, finally fixing with a glue gun.</p>\r\n'),(1088,'<p>Now that the &lsquo;Star Ceiling&rsquo; was built, tested and installed, it was time to lift the Hobbit Hole one last time and drop it into it&rsquo;s final resting place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The hole was lined with 1mm plastic as damp proofing, with the structure then placed inside of that, I continued to wrap the whole structure in the same plastic, excluding the front wall. I then used sections from an old chopped up glass fibre pond to help add extra strength and seal the top. Sealing the floor, I used concrete. Thankfully, when it came to filling the base and exteriors outer edges with roughly 200mm of concrete, we had my partners nephew, George, staying who saved a lot of heat, sweat and red faces - good man!</p>\r\n'),(1089,'<p>While the concrete we laid it in the morning was left to set and harden, during the afternoon, George and I decided to dig and run armoured cable into the Hobbit Hole. Throughout the week, I moved onto building and installing a Hobbit style door, sealed the exposed Plywood with liquid damp proofing and finally started to pile earth around the rear and sides. To control the lighting and ensure there were no exposed switches for the children, I tucked all the electrical components and connections away in a secure wall box, fitted with a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.lightwaverf.com/solution/smart-home/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"LightwaveRF\">LightwaveRF</a> inline relay. This meant we could control the lighting by remote or through our smartphones.</p>\r\n'),(1090,'<p>Moving on, now that the concrete had set and safe enough to climb inside, it was time to decorate and create a feature wall. I decided on creating a feature wall which involved log slices, so I set-up the cradle and fired the McCulloch chainsaw into life. Cutting each slice of already seasoned wood at approximately the same thickness. In total,&nbsp;cut roughly 2 large buckets to have enough to completly cover the rear wall.&nbsp;</p>\r\n'),(1091,'<p>Before the slices were placed onto the wall, I ensured any dust was brushed off. I got myself 3 tubes of &#39;Sticks Like&#39;&nbsp;<strike>shit</strike> and started slapping them onto the rear wall in a random like pattern. I continued through and finished the feature wall, as well as covering the external liquid damp proofing with artificial grass, and found an old vintage light to hang outside the front which I filled with the remaining &#39;Star Ceiling&rsquo; LED lights. I was very VERY happy with how this turned out and how the whole thing was looking, admittedly, I was defiantly more excited at this point than our daughters were.</p>\r\n'),(1092,'<p>The Interior was now complete and working, it was damp proofed and grass was slowly but surely starting to growing on the roof and up the sides. Things were working out great! I now needed to cover the exposed blue plastic wrap around the front, doing so with an old corrugated roofing sheet. Cut to size and overlapped, secured with concrete, expandable foam and pop rivets - and finally finished off with a lick of brown paint to help blend in and look natural. I also created 2 log retaining walls to help hold back the earth, held together by large pins that are put through every log and then into the ground.</p>\r\n'),(1093,'<h2><strong>Thoughts on the final outcome</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Fast forward over 6 months, I&rsquo;m happy with how things look and worked out. This wasn&rsquo;t a step-by-step planned projects, it was merely a &quot;make it up as you go along&quot; kind of project with no deadlines, which was nice. Projects like this give you the opportunity to chop and change ideas as you go, but can also allow you to forget to do things that you should of done - but lucky for me I hadn&rsquo;t&hellip; I think?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The grass hasn&rsquo;t fully grown yet and is still a tad patchy, but it will grow in time. My partner has recently planted strawberries and scattered coloured wild flower seeds, so next year things should look even better. This is the type of project that looks better and more natural as time goes on, when nature tries to take over again. What do you think?</p>\r\n'),(1096,'<blockquote class=\"instagram-media\" data-instgrm-captioned data-instgrm-version=\"7\" style=\" background:#FFF; border:0; border-radius:3px; box-shadow:0 0 1px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.5),0 1px 10px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.15); margin: 1px; max-width:658px; padding:0; width:99.375%; width:-webkit-calc(100% - 2px); width:calc(100% - 2px);\"><div style=\"padding:8px;\"> <div style=\" background:#F8F8F8; line-height:0; margin-top:40px; padding:50.0% 0; text-align:center; width:100%;\"> <div style=\" background:url(data:image/png;base64,); display:block; height:44px; margin:0 auto -44px; position:relative; top:-22px; width:44px;\"></div></div> <p style=\" margin:8px 0 0 0; padding:0 4px;\"> <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/BWOGnMjDMXJ/\" style=\" color:#000; font-family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:17px; text-decoration:none; word-wrap:break-word;\" target=\"_blank\">Finishing off a spot of work in the garden, enjoying the cool breezes and actually using the garden lights, which we very rarely use - another bliss moment. #designer #garden #gardenporn #lighting #lightingdesign #playhouse #kids #family #entrepreneur #solopreneur #nightshift #night #nightsky #landscape #hobbit #hob